\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>Three years in ward F had tailored Lucy to be modest, considerate - yet confident in her work. <#/>As she came into the ward, today she 
noticed a new occupant in bed thirteen. <#/>Lucy glanced at the temperature chart that hung on the wall at the head of the bed. <#/>The patient's name was there, Alice Gakenia.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 "Gakenia," Lucy called. <#/>"How are you?" <#/>This was the trick in the ho
spital. <#/>Always talk to the patients as if you had known them for a long time. <#/>Every nurse had learnt that trick of reading the name on the temperature chart and then calling the patient with all the familiarity one could force into one's voice. <#
/>But, of course, there were a few embarrassing situations when the wrong temperature chart hung by a bedside. <#/>This was not the case this time, for the patient in bed thirteen responded happily.
\par <#/>"I am fine, although I don't feel that well," she said.
\par <#/>"Give me your hand, Alice," Lucy said in a soothing voice, genuinely caring and without any air of condescension. <#/>Lucy took Gakenia's wrist and proceeded to count her pulse.
\par <#/>"What is it this time'?" Sister Maingi asked. <#/>Lucy was startled. <#/>Barely ten seconds had passed since she had taken Gakenia's arm.
\par <#/>"Lucy!" Sister Maingi roared and the ward almost shook. <#/>It was amazing how sister Maingi could roar. <#/>The nurses always gossiped that any woman who arrived in hospital before 
she was in labour was immediately gripped by unbearable labour pains on hearing the rumbling of Sister Maingi. <#/>The truth of this was never verified, though it sounded quite convincing. <#/>Lucy stopped in the middle of her counting and attended to Sis
ter Maingi.
\par <#/>"Look here, my child." <#/>Sister Maingi's voice became more gentle seeing the tension on Lucy's face. <#/>"You never examine any patient while standing on the left side of the bed."
\par <#/>Lucy had forgotten this taboo, and quickly went round to the right side of the bed.
\par <#/>"And, Lucy, you are to listen to the foetal heart every ten minutes for bed thirteen."
\par <#/>"But it is always done every fifteen minutes, Sister," Lucy said shyly trying to sound right for once.
\par <#/>"This isn't an average c
ase, so do as I say." Lucy did not ask why. <#/>In the ward, you are supposed to know things, not learn them. <#/>You learn in the nursing school. <#/>After the first readings, Lucy went back to the Sister's desk to record the findings in Gakenia's case s
h
eet. <#/>It was then she noticed a few details about Gakenia. <#/>This was her second pregnancy. <#/>The first pregnancy had ended in a caesarean section and now Gakenia had a trivial scar. <#/>She was of medium height and her pelvic assessment by Dr. Dav
e had been promising.
\par <#/>Ten minutes later, Gakenia was having quite frequent contractions of moderate strength and she asked Lucy, "Do you think I will have an easy delivery?"
\par <#/>"Well, you should if Dr. Dave thinks you will."
\par <#/>"I would not like to lose this baby."
\par <#/>"Did you lose the other one?" Lucy asked.
\par <#/>"Not during birth. <#/>She died a few hours after I was operated on. <#/>The doctor said it had suffered some damage before the operation."
\par <#/>"I am sorry to hear that, but this one will be fine."
\par <#/>"Do you love babies?"
\par <#/>"Every woman does," said Lucy.
\par <#/>"I don't think every woman does. <#/>When I talk even to women about my great desire to have a baby, they say I am madly in love with babies."
\par <#/>"It is all right to love babies. <#/>Now lie on your back. <#/>I want to hear if your baby is OK. <#/>Lucy waited for the contractions to subside to listen to the foetal heart. <#/>Tap-tap-tap... the heartbeat went. <#/>And she counted on - a hundred 
and forty-six, a hundred and fifty, a hundred and sixty-six!
\par <#/>"Sister Maingi!"
\par <#/>Why had she shouted? <#/>Gakenia might get scared.
\par <#/>"What is the matter? <#/>Isn't the baby all right?" asked Gakenia.
\par <#/>"Oh well... it's just a little thing."
\par <#/>"What has happened?" Sister Maingi shouted back.
\par <#/>"I think there is a foetal distress. <#/>The foetal heart rate is one hundred and sixty-six."
\par <#/>"What?" <#/>Now Sister Maingi was going to cause an earthquake. <#/>"Call the doctor." <#/>Sister Maingi was now louder than thunder.
\par <#/>"Speak softly," Lucy said. <#/>"The doctor is just in the next ward." <#/>It was now Lucy who retained that complacency and coolness of a medical staff. <#/>This was the golden rule in the hospital. <#/>Keep cool even if your
 clothes are on fire. <#/>And Lucy kept cool. <#/>She went to the next ward and talked to Dr. Dave.
\par <#/>"Doctor, the foetal heart rate in bed thirteen is a hundred and sixty-six."
\par <#/>"Is it regular?" asked Dr. Dave, his voice cooler than ice-cream.
\par <#/>"Yes, it is."
\par <#/>"Let's go over and have a look, young lady." <#/>They walked to the maternity ward. <#/>They found Sister Maingi frantic. <#/>Trying to confirm Lucy's finding, she was leaning on poor Gakenia's tummy, striving to listen to the foetal heart.
 <#/>Sister Maingi had the foetalscope the wrong way up!
\par <#/>"I think it has disappeared," she murmured.
\par <#/>"What has disappeared?" asked Dr. Dave.
\par <#/>"The foetal heartbeat," Sister Maingi groaned.
\par <#/>"No, I don't think so," said Dr. Dave gently, pulling Sister Maingi away. <#/>He listened for a few minutes and counted every one of those gentle tap-tap-taps.
\par <#/>"I agree, Lucy. <#/>There may be foetal distress here. <#/>Bring me a couple of gloves and the screens. <#/>I want to assess the descent of the presenting part."
\par <#/>Lucy went over to the sterile store and came back with gloves number nine. <#/>Everyone in the hospital knew that Dr. Dave wore gloves number nine. <#/>Dr. Dave had by far the largest hands in the hospital. <#/>It was no wonder. <#/>H
e was six feet three and built like a wrestler. <#/>At first sight you would never have thought he was a doctor. <#/>But he had brains, and his dexterity in surgery was unequalled. <#/>Bearing in mind his size, his manners and voice were sheer irony. <#/>
H
e had a rare, soft missionary voice. <#/>His manners were gentle and suited the mission well. <#/>Many called him Saint Francis incarnate. <#/>He was the life of the hospital, for he was the one who set the hopeful mood and pace. <#/>As for his faith, the
re was no question of it being anything short of genuine. <#/>Every elder in and around the hospital never saw any better example of a missionary. <#/>If Dr. Dave fell, then the hospital would also fall.
\par <#/>Dr. Dave put on the gloves without any ceremony. <#/>When it came to action, he never wasted any time.
\par <#/>"Head presenting, but there has been no descent for the last hour. <#/>Sister, call theatre and tell them to prepare for a section." The Sister passed the order to Lucy.
\par <#/>"Lucy, call theatre and tell them to prepare for a section."
\par <#/>"Thank you, Sister." Lucy was busy on the phone. <#/>"They say they will be ready in half an hour. <#/>They are informing the theatre sister," Lucy reported.
\par <#/>"Now go and continue with the observation of bed thirteen," Sister said as she followed the doctor out.
\par <#/>Lucy was left alone taking Gakenia's temperature, pulse rate, respiration rate and foetal heart rate as required. <#/>She was uneasy. <#/>Something was going wrong. <#/>She knew how Gakenia valued this
 baby and inwardly prayed that God would give it to her. <#/>It dawned on Lucy that she loved Gakenia for a reason she could not define. <#/>She looked at Gakenia's face and saw agony and anguish. <#/>Was she in such pain or was she afraid, afraid of losi
n
g this baby? She dared not ask. <#/>She was just slightly older than Lucy by the looks of her. <#/>Possibly this was why Lucy was so sympathetic towards her. <#/>No, this could not be the reason. <#/>Why then? Possibly it was because Gakenia had such a fa
c
e as reminded her of her mother. <#/>Was it because she too would obviously have to experience the same pangs of child-birth at one time? She did not know. <#/>Or could it be that there is an unconscious love that ties all beings of a similar nature to ea
ch other, making each feel the pain of the other? Whatever it was, Lucy was feeling the pain of Gakenia.
\par <#/>Forty minutes, and still no call from the theatre. <#/>The foetal heart rate was coming down. <#/>One hundred and twenty, one hundred and sixteen... <#/>Lucy called Dr. Dave over the phone. <#/>He was already in the theatre.
\par <#/>"Doctor, the foetal heart rate is a hundred and sixteen."
\par <#/>"Is it? <#/>Bring the patient over immediately."
\par <#/>"We have not yet contacted the theatre doctor."
\par <#/>"This is an emergency and we shall not wait."
\par <#/>"I know a bit about theatre. <#/>I think I'll come and assist," Lucy said confidently. <#/>She felt confident not because she knew she could handle the situation, but because she was ready to do everything possible to help Gakenia.
\par <#/>In less than five minutes, Gakenia was in the theatre. <#/>Lucy had mobilised all the labour-ward nurses, the stretcher had been available and Gakenia practically airlifted to the theatre.
\par <#/>"Carry on, Lucy," Lucy heard Dr. Dave say.
\par <#/>"He cannot mean it," she thought. <#/>"I was offering to help in handing over the sterile instruments, but not to assist the doctor."
\par <#/>"Quicker, Lucy. <#/>Time is short. <#/>And you over there, keep listening to the foetal heart. <#/>T
ell the patient not to push. <#/>She already has a scar." Gakenia was pushing hard now. <#/>"Do not push, young girl!" said Dr. Dave. <#/>There was a note of panic now even in Dr. Dave's voice. <#/>"Please, don't push!" <#/>But who can make a woman in lab
o
ur stop pushing? It is like swallowing only to be told not to swallow it when it is halfway down the throat. <#/>One cannot stop. <#/>One goes on swallowing. <#/>You do not even listen. <#/>Gakenia kept on pushing. <#/>She wished she could obey the doctor
, but she felt an irresistible urge to push.
\par <#/>"Don't push!" Dr. Dave at last shouted. <#/>"Get on, you, Mary. <#/>Give the anaesthesia."
\par <#/>There was real danger now. <#/>If the anaesthetist delayed any longer, Gakenia was going to rupture her uterus...
 <#/>and she did! <#/>She gave a loud gasp and clasped her abdomen with her hands. <#/>Blood streamed down between her legs and the nurse checking the foetal heart reported no heartbeat. <#/>It was too late. <#/>Or was it?
\par <#/>"What shall I do now, sir?" Mary, the anaesthetist, asked.
\par <#/>"Just go ahead and give the anaesthesia. <#/>We have to fight to save the mother if not the child as well." And the operation began.
\par <#/>Lucy was on the other side mopping up the blood, pulling that artery forceps and the 
other! <#/>She clamped the bleeding one and got ready to clamp the weak one. <#/>Now it was time to cut the suture and hand the doctor the retractor. <#/>They were now in the abdominal cavity. <#/>The whole area was full of blood. <#/>Gakenia must have bl
ed a lot.
\par <#/>"She has lost a lot of blood," Lucy said.
\par <#/>"Yes," said the doctor. <#/>"One of you girls there, fix an intravenous drip on the other hand." <#/>That was done.
\par <#/>Dr. Dave was now fishing out the baby entangled in the mess of blood. <#/>The
re was only one hope. <#/>If the placenta was still attached, the baby could still live. <#/>The uterus was not fully contracted and that was the first sign of hope. <#/>A linear tear was visible at the place of the old scar. <#/>"Let's get busy and open 
the uterus fully." <#/>Lucy's fingers met now and then with Dr. Dave's as they struggled to open the uterus. <#/>They pulled out the baby and it gave a very feeble cry.
\par <#/>"Clamp the cord, Lucy." <#/>Lucy clamped the cord twice and cut it out. <#/>"Go ahea
d and resuscitate the baby." <#/>Lucy took away the child to the resuscitating machine. <#/>It was a difficult job sucking out all that mucus and blood from its mouth. <#/>She worked with such enthusiasm that one would have thought that it was a baby from
 her own womb. <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 She sucked and sucked the baby's mouth, slapped the baby and directed a strong jet of oxygen into its face five times. <#/>She got no further cry from the baby.
\par <#/>"Sodium bicarbonate, nurse!" Lucy called. <#/>She had now become the doct
or, giving orders. <#/>But had she done these things before? <#/>They were coming so clearly in her memory. <#/>The sodium bicarbonate was brought and Lucy forced it into the umbilical vein.
\par <#/>Ten minutes... <#/>still no regular breathing. <#/>Gasp, gasp
, irregular gasps, and still no regular breathing. <#/>She should call the doctor but he was operating and the second doctor was off duty. <#/>She was now at the end of her tether. <#/>She had fully exhausted her nurse's knowledge on how to initiate regul
a
r breathing in an anoxic child. <#/>But she vaguely remembered when Sister Maingi had introduced a tube into a baby's trachea and flushed oxygen into the lungs rhythmically. <#/>The baby had lived. <#/>But Sister Maingi was a Sister and Lucy was only an e
n
rolled nurse! Even in life-saving procedures, there were rules of job description. <#/>The only alternative was to call Sister Maingi. <#/>What nonsense! <#/>To call Sister Maingi to theatre would require a whole day of waiting. <#/>She would have to chan
ge into theatre clothes, which for Sister Maingi would take hours! <#/>(She was so clumsy when it came to undressing and dressing that the nurses always wondered how many hours she usually took to dress at home.)
\par <#/>Lucy decided not to call Sister Maingi. 
<#/>She might as well have signed a mortuary form for the baby. <#/>She loved this baby very much and was going to do everything possible to save it. <#/>She was going to push in that tube just as Sister Maingi had done.
\par <#/>"Which tube do you mean?" quest
ioned the nurse she had sent. <#/>Lucy had actually forgotten the name of the instrument, but after repeating "Not that one," she succeeded in getting the right tube. <#/>In a minute or two, Lucy had slipped the tube into the baby's wind-pipe and was read
y
 for the action of pumping in and out of the little infant's lungs. <#/>Lucy's face shone as she saw the infant's chest heave up and down. <#/>Here was the breath of life oxygen rushing right into the lungs. <#/>Very soon the heaves became regular. <#/>Th
e
 heartbeat also, previously wild, was now regular. <#/>The baby's colour changed from heavenly blue to the dark brown of the rich soil of volcanic highlands. <#/>Here were the signs of life. <#/>Here was life itself. <#/>Ten more minutes and Lucy had to r
e
move this bothersome tube to let the baby cry. <#/>The baby had been saved. <#/>The miracle had been performed. <#/>By Lucy? <#/>No. <#/>This was a mission hospital. <#/>The miracle was by God, and Lucy was only an instrument in the hands of the Almighty.
 <#/>But the other nurses were convinced that Lucy was solely responsible for saving the child.
\par <#/>On the other side, Dr. Dave was still fighting with Gakenia's blood vessels, which were threatening to bleed the life out of her. <#/>He was now closing the 
abdominal wall. <#/>The uterus had been sutured. <#/>It was very risky to have a ruptured uterus inside a fertile woman. <#/>That would be inviting the same disaster twice. <#/>The uterus had been removed, and with it the end of Gakenia's hope of another 
c
hild. <#/>But poor Gakenia knew nothing of this as she lay there, calm and peaceful. <#/>One hour past the normal hospital duty time, Lucy was sitting next to Gakenia in the intensive care unit. <#/>Two pints of blood were flowing into her veins, thanks t
o
 that genius who discovered blood transfusion. <#/>She was even capable of talking now. <#/>She had overheard a bit of the nurses gossiping as they talked of Lucy's miracle in saving her baby. <#/>The whole story was running from one ward to another in su
ch a speed as supersedes U.S. <#/>presidential election results. <#/>Even the cooks knew before Gakenia left the hospital that it was Lucy who had rescued Gakenia's baby from the hideous jaws of death.
\par <#/>Gakenia was talking to Lucy.
\par <#/>"Who is Lucy?" she asked. <#/>All this while, Gakenia did not know the name of the nurse who had spent the most time attending her.
\par <#/>"Lucy who?" Lucy asked.
\par <#/>"I don't know her other name, but everybody says that she is the one who saved my child."
\par <#/>"Oh, I see. <#/>I'll introduce her to you when you get well." <#/>She smiled shyly.
\par <#/>"I am so happy that the child is alive. <#/>I pray to God to keep her for a hundred years."
\par <#/>"He surely will," Lucy said.
\par <#/>"And then I'll give her a brother and possibly a sister."
\par <#/>What was that she said? <#/>Lucy's heart wept inside. <#/>Give her a brother? A sister? <#/>Who will ever explain her operation to her? <#/>Lucy's eyes were becoming wet. <#/>"I am happy you came through. <#/>It was also a difficult time for you."

\par <#/>"Yes," said Gakenia. <#/>"I'll still go through it again for another baby. <#/>I would risk anything for a sweet baby."
\par <#/>That was enough for Lucy. <#/>"Now I have to go," she said. <#/>"I'll see you tonight."}{\fs24\lang2057 </X>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
