\par <I> <h> <#/>I cannot sign </h>
\par <#/>"I cannot sign."
\par <#/>"Why not?"
\par <#/>"I just can't."
\par <#/>"Why not?"
\par <#/>"Her children."
\par <#/>"What about them?"
\par <#/>"Their mother's blood will be on my head. <#/>They will suffer. <#/>Our husband is already on trial. <#/>He might be hanged and the children will be orphans. <#/>I couldn't live with that."
\par <#/>"Do you know how many people she has <slang/>gotten killed?"
\par <#/>"I know, but I don't want to be like her. <#/>If we cannot sympathize with her children, who also call me mother, then we have no business fighting for freedom."
\par <#/>"You know she could get you killed."
\par <#/>"Yes, she has tried already, but I shall not sign to have my children's mother's blood shed. <#/>You can kill me, but I will not sign."
\par <#/>The freedom fighters looked at each other, before telling Wanjiru to go out while they decided what to do. <#/>As she stood in the outer room of the freedom fighters' house at Milimani, her mind went back to the day when the whole thing started.

\par <#/>The day before the Lari massacre, she had given birth to a baby girl. <#/>The baby had died immediately after birth and since it was those bad times, no ceremonies were held. <#/>She remembered 
that Mr. <#/>Mbugua, who was a distant relative and a neighbour, had buried the baby for her. <#/>Her husband was in Nairobi doing business and now that the Emergency had started, he preferred to stay in town where he felt it was safer.
\par <#/>The night after
 the baby was buried, the Lari massacre began. <#/>Wanjiru was alone in the house with her five children, aged between two and twelve. <#/>She heard the screaming of suffering people and saw the blazing of houses on fire. <#/>She instructed her children n
ot to get out of bed.
\par <#/>"If we have to die, let us die together," she told them.
\par <#/>They waited for the morning, which took a very long time to come. <#/>Every few minutes, she'd ask her eldest son, "Waweru, have you heard the cock crow?"
\par <#/>"No, mother."
\par <#/>After a long, frightening wait, the morning came. <#/>The children stood at the door to see what was going on. <#/>They reported to the mother that there was a lot of movement going on. <#/>People were carrying their children and property away. <#/>
Their two step-mothers were doing the same. <#/>Waweru came and said, \ldblquote Mother, everybody is leaving."
\par <#/>"Waweru, I can't even move out of bed. <#/>Come closer."
\par <#/>The boy went to the bed where his sick mother lay.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>"You see, we shall have to wait until I am a little better. <#/>Now I am very weak. <#/>If I get out of bed, I will collapse. <#/>Get the children together and pray."
\par <#/>Waweru brought the other four children. <#/>As they knelt by the mother's bed, Waweru prayed. <#/>"God, our Father, make our mother well. <#/>We have to get out of here because we might be killed. <#/>We ask you this in Jesus' name."
\par <#/>"Amen," they all said.
\par <#/>The children then went outside. <#/>But a few minutes later, a hail of bullets sent them running back i
n. <#/>There was shooting everywhere, so they locked themselves in the house. <#/>The only other sound that could be heard was that of Wanjiru groaning with pain. <#/>The children huddled together in fear and waited for the shooting to stop.
\par <#/>After abou
t an hour, it stopped. <#/>Waweru went outside the house to get some firewood. <#/>Maybe a cup of tea for his mother might ease the pains. <#/>He lit the fire, and the smoke could be seen from very far away. <#/>Beth, coming back from taking her children 
t
o safer ground, saw the smoke. <#/>She had heard that Wanjiru had had a baby who had died. <#/>She decided to go there and find out what was going on. <#/>She was not afraid because the home guards knew she was not a Mau Mau. <#/>The Mau Mau also knew tha
t she never reported anybody. <#/>She was a staunch Christian. <#/>She just went to church and prayed that the war would end.
\par <#/>She knocked at the door and Waweru opened it.
\par <#/>"Waweru, what are you doing here?"
\par <#/>The boy kept quiet.
\par <#/>"Where is your mother?"
\par <#/>"She is lying on the bed. <#/>She is very sick."
\par <#/>Beth went into the hut and straight to the bed. <#/>"Wanjiru, sorry about the baby. <#/>It is God's will. <#/>Now you have to get up. <#/>Everybody has left this ridge. <#/>Things are very 
bad. <#/>I have taken my children to safety and I was coming to get a few things when I saw smoke in your house."
\par <#/>Wanjiru replied to her, "I can't get up. <#/>I have been bleeding since the baby came. <#/>I have eaten nothing and I am weak and in pain.
 <#/>Do me a favour. <#/>Just escort my children to my mother's place so that they can be safe. <#/>If you take them as far as Ruiru, Waweru will then lead them to their grandmother."
\par <#/>"I will do that, then I will come back. <#/>If you are still alive, I will then take you to safety."
\par <#/>Just then, Waweru brought in two cups of tea. <#/>Beth said, "Good boy. <#/>Now, leave the two cups for your mother and tell the other children to get ready. <#/>Take two pairs of shorts and shirts for the boys and two 
dresses each for the girls. <#/>I shall escort you to Ruiru after which you can go to your grandmother's."
\par <#/>"What about mother?"
\par <#/>"I shall come back for her."
\par <#/>"No, you take the other children. <#/>I will wait here with mother," said Waweru.
\par <#/>"No, I cannot do that because when we reach Ruiru, they cannot find their way on their own," said Beth, indicating with her hands that she meant the other children.
\par <#/>"OK, let's hurry then, so you can come back for my mother."
\par <#/>Beth and the children found their way to the grandmother's house. <#/>After a few days, Beth managed to take Wanjiru to Ruiru to join her children and mother.
\par <#/>In this house there were many other people who had run away from homes that were near the forests for fear of being accused of harbouring the Mau Mau, especially after the Lari massacre.
\par <#/>Wanjiru slept until she had recovered her strength. <#/>She was still very tired, but here, her mother and her sisters took care of her. <#/>They fed her whatever they could find. <#
/>Soon after, the shooting and general harassment that had taken place in Lari started anew, this time in Limuru. <#/>She remembered that three homes where they were staying were burnt. <#/>The Mau Mau were supposed to have been in there.
\par <#/>Two days late
r, Wanjiru's husband sent a message that she should bring the children with her to Nairobi. <#/>The co-wife had told the colonial government that the Mau Mau had been sharpening their knives in Wanjiru's house, so the home guards were looking for her.

\par <#/>
Wanjiru was therefore smuggled into Nairobi with her children. <#/>By now she was feeling a little better, and when they arrived, she was able to feed the children. <#/>She was staying near Mlango Kubwa. <#/>On the same compound, there were many other wom
en who had been smuggled out of the countryside to protect them from home guards.
\par <#/>She stayed with her husband for three days, after which he was arrested and taken to Githunguri for trial. <#/>The case went on for over one and a half years and finally h
er husband was acquitted of the <-/>offense, thanks to his Indian lawyer. <#/>He was, however, detained.
\par <#/>During their time in Nairobi, the urban Mau Mau guerrillas used to come to their compound for a meal. <#/>She and the other women would feed them, 
and then they would leave. <#/>Two of them who came frequently were identified by Wanjiru's co-wife, who reported to the home guards. <#/>The next time they came for lunch, the two Mau Mau men were ambushed and arrested.
\par <#/>Wanjiru's tears flowed down her cheeks as she remembered that terrible day. <#/>The two men were beaten so badly that as they were being taken by the soldiers, they were as good as dead. <#/>They could not talk or move or even see.
\par <#/>The women on the compound looked on. <#/>The two me
n were put in a van, and the soldiers came back. <#/>They started beating the women, even the pregnant ones, asking them why they had not reported to the police. <#/>Two of them lost their babies as a result, not to mention their own lives.
\par <#/>While all this was happening, Wanjiru was standing at the door of her room holding on to her two-year-old baby girl. <#/>The soldiers kept asking the rest of the women, "Who is Wanjiru?"
\par <#/>"We don't know her."
\par <#/>Nobody said that Wanjiru was standing there. <#/>On
e of the soldiers came and took Wanjiru's baby. <#/>He threatened to throw the baby down if the other women did not identify Wanjiru. <#/>Just then, the baby clutched on to the baby's nose. <#/>`Maybe the nose looked strange, as if it could be plucked out
,' thought Wanjiru. <#/>The soldier looked at the baby, who was still holding on to his nose, and then gave the baby back to its mother. <#/>He told the other soldiers that that was enough for the day.
\par <#/>Minutes later, a car with Mau Mau fighters came and took the bodies of the women away. <#/>Soon after they left, another car came for Wanjiru and her children. <#/>\ldblquote 
We have to take you away to safety. <#/>They will come back for you before nightfall or at night.\rdblquote 
\par <#/>Wanjiru took her children and got into the car. <#/>She was taken to another house in Eastleigh. <#/>From there, she used to go to court to listen to her husband\rquote s case. <#/>It was when she was there that two men were sent from the Mau Mau 
office in Milimani to get her to sign that Mau Mau should get rid of her co-wife.
\par <#/>\ldblquote Come back, Wanjiru, \ldblquote  a voice said from the other room.
\par <#/>Wanjiru entered the room where the Mau Mau fighters were deliberating. <#/>One of them said to her, \ldblquote We have 
reached a verdict. <#/>We cannot kill you, as you asked us to do. <#/>You are one of us and we cannot destroy ourselves. <#/>We shall not kill your co-wife either, since you have reasoned with us. <#/>We shall protect you as much as we can. <#/>We will, h
owever carry out various activities to threaten and intimidate your co-wife so that she stops her activities. <#/>Agreed?
