ildren, bearing striking resemblance to their father, pleaded with him not to abandon them. <#/>The bride burst into tears and was consoled by her maids. <#/>The congregation was shocked.
\par <#/>Kui's earlier anger returned. <#/>This time she was angry with wo
men. <#/>Some women. <#/>Neither those who married traditionally like her mother not those who married in church like the one whose aborted marriage she had just been reading about. <#/>She was angry with those who were better informed. <#/>The lawyers. <
#/>They were the ones who understood the confusion of multiple marriage laws in the country and the pain it was causing in families. <#/>Why were they so quiet about it? <#/>Are human rights only political? <#/>Are they not social as well?
\par <#/>Kui made a promise, `I shall train as a lawyer. <#/>I shall strive to get a B average grade to qualify to go to the university. <#/>then I shall educate my fellow women on where they stand as regards the law on marriage.'</X>
