\par <#/>I heard the scream. <#/>I shot out of sleep with a jerk. <#/>It was after waking up that I thought I must have
 been dreaming. <#/>But it came again. <#/>A blood-chilling scream. <#/>I immediately thought of my daughter, Anne, who had been having nightmares lately.
\par <#/>"Anne! <#/>Anne! <#/>What is it?" I called out, panic-stricken. <#/>Before she responded I heard 
another scream, this time more deafening and frightening than before. <#/>I jumped out of bed and rushed to Anne's bedroom. <#/>To my relief, she was deeply asleep and seemed least disturbed. <#/>Another desperate scream pierced my ears. <#/>It came from 
outside the house. <#/>I hurried out to the living room wondering who it could be.
\par <#/>Then I remembered Lucy, my friend and neighbour, who had been having problems with her husband. <#/>I tiptoed to open the windows in the living room to ascertain the dire
ction of the screams. <#/>When the next scream came, it confirmed my worst fears. <#/>Lucy was in trouble and needed help. <#/>But I dared not venture to her house because her husband was quite a violent man. <#/>He had a strong dislike for women, particu
larly Lucy's friends.
\par <#/>I walked back to our bedroom. <#/>My husband, Joe, was awake. <#/>When I asked him to go and assist Lucy, he seemed reluctant to intervene because he knew Lucy's husband and his violent nature. <#/>He was certain that when Jared, L
ucy's husband, was in that murderous state, he was capable of doing anything.
\par <#/>Jared was known to be unfaithful to his wife but he tried to cover up this by accusing Lucy of unfaithfulness. <#/>My husband was not willing to intervene because Jared would
 accuse him of being one of Lucy's lovers. <#/>I tried to persuade Joe that what was at stake was more serious than what Jared might do to him but he would not budge.
\par <#/>Suddenly, there was a loud <-/desparate> bang on our back door. <#/>I rushed to the door, switched on the security light and who should I see standing out there but Lucy! <#/>Stark naked! <#/>I could not believe my eyes. <#/>I was trembling as I opene
d
 the door for her. <#/>She had scratches all over her body. <#/>One of her eyes was swollen. <#/>Blood was oozing from her nose and mouth. <#/>Her hair was dishevelled. <#/>There were so many bruises on her body that it looked as if a witchdoctor had perf
ormed numerous rituals on her. <#/>Her grotesque appearance sent a chill down my spine. <#/>It was a surprise that she could stand, let alone walk.
\par <#/>Her three-year-old daughter who also had blood on her body clutched at her chest like a tick. <#/>She too
 was naked. <#/>It was a truly horrifying sight. <#/>As I stared at them dumbfounded, Joe coughed. <#/>This brought me back to reality and I hastily pulled them in, locked the door and leaned against it as if to ensure that Lucy's husband did not enter.

\par <#/>"Please, tell Baba Anne not to come out of the bedroom," Lucy pleaded. <#/>I nodded understandingly and rushed to the bedroom to pass on the message.
\par <#/>"Don't come out! <#/>Lucy is nude!" I shouted as I looked for a dress that could fit her.
\par <#/>"What?
" Joe asked perplexed as if he did not know that Jared was capable of doing anything when he was angry. <#/>I did not answer him. <#/>I dashed out of the bedroom with a light-blue free-size dress for Lucy. <#/>This was the only dress that could fit her si
nce she was a little bigger than me. <#/>As she painfully struggled to slip it on, I looked for some warm clothing for her daughter and helped the little girl to dress.
\par <#/>I was preparing to light the gas cooker to warm some water for first aid when I reme
mbered that the gas had run out earlier that evening. <#/>I quickly turned to the paraffin stove. <#/>But just then I remembered that I had kept a thermos flask full of hot water for use the following morning. <#/>I took some of this water, poured it into
 a basin and carefully cleaned Lucy's face. <#/>I massaged it gently as she was pointing out the most painful areas. <#/>I applied some liniment to the affected areas. <#/>I cleaned her daughter too.
\par <#/>All this while, Lucy had been sobbing quietly, her ch
est heaving up and down. <#/>When I prepared some coffee for her, she refused to take it and sat there cursing her fate in low tones. <#/>I tried to console her but it seemed that this time she had suffered more than ever before. <#/>I could understand th
e
 anguish, strain and the feeling of helplessness she was experiencing. <#/>This was not the first time Jared had battered Lucy. <#/>Apart from coming home drunk and disturbing the whole neighbourhood with his shouting, he fought over prostitutes, went in 
a
nd out of police cells for drinking traditional liquor and quarrelled with Lucy for `befriending men indiscriminately'. <#/>He would repeatedly beat her up and then disappear for weeks. <#/>It did not come as a surprise this time to see Lucy really broken
 down.
\par <#/>"Lucy," I addressed her.
\par <#/>"Yeeee-ee-s," she whispered reluctantly with a lot of pain both on her body and in her thoughts.
\par <#/>"What happened this time?"
\par <#/>There was no answer, either because her voice failed her or she thought the question needed no answer.
\par <#/>"Lucy," I called again.
\par <#/>There was now no response from her.
\par <#/>"There is a very close friend of mine who went through a myriad of traumatic experience like yours," I continued. <#/>"There was no week that passed without her recei
ving a thorough beating from her husband." Lucy looked up with interest, struggling to open her swollen eye.
\par <#/>"During one of their fights, she lost two of her upper teeth. <#/>This was the worst of her experiences. <#/>But surprisingly, they later made up and struggled on with their life together," I concluded.
\par <#/>On hearing this, Lucy brightened up a bit but soon started sobbing again. <#/>I did not try to stop her. <#/>I took her daughter who was already asleep on her lap to my children's bedroom. <#/>When I came back, she had stopped sobbing.
\par <#/>It seemed like she wanted to say something but did not know how to begin. <#/>She shifted in her seat but this made her groan painfully. <#/>Her knees were beginning to swell so I gave her the liniment to apply on them.
\par <#/>"Mama Anne," she started in a shaky but determined voice. <#/>"I - I have never told you this before. <#/>My parents separated and eventually divorced when I was still very young," she said.
\par <#/>"Hm-Hm-Hm-" I nodded encouragingly.
\par <#/>"I gr
ew up in the cruel hands of a stepmother," she continued. <#/>"My father was very loving but he was not with us most of the time. <#/>I know very well what it means to be discriminated against in one's own home! <#/>I was harassed and beaten for no reason
. <#/>I went to school only when my stepmother wished. <#/>I almost starved! <#/>Hunger would lead me into stealing and as a result I would be thoroughly beaten."
\par <#/>"Poor thing!" I responded.
\par <#/>"When I was sixteen and just about to complete my second ye
ar in high school, I met Jared. <#/>He was a very charming and handsome young man - a teacher then. <#/>I was attracted to him. <#/>I saw in this man a saviour. <#/>He was gentle and talked to me lovingly. <#/>I saw in this man a solution to all my proble
ms. <#/>I believed that Jared was all I needed in the world. <#/>I do not think any amount of pressure would have pulled me away from him," Lucy paused to cough and groaned with the effort. <#/>I just watched her, not wanting to interrupt.
\par <#/>"Before I knew what was going on, I was pregnant," she said.
\par <#/>"What was your parents' reaction?" I asked.
\par <#/>"My father was mad with me. <#/>He went wild like a wounded buffalo! <#/>He raged with hostility. <#/>I never knew I could survive the beating he gave me. <
#/>He forced Jared to marry me and threatened to sue him if he refused to do so. <#/>For fear of what might befall him, he married me. <#/>I felt overjoyed.
\par <#/>"One year after our marriage, Jared married Winnie as a second wife. <#/>She was a university u
ndergraduate. <#/>I hung on despite the pressure exerted on me because polygamy was not strange to me. <#/>Soon after she graduated and got a job, she left Jared because of his cruelty.
\par <#/>"One bright afternoon, Jared took me by surprise when after leaving the house, he returned shortly with several of his male colleagues. <#/>He started shouting at me to leave his house, accusing me of being a whore.
\par <#/>"His colleagues were surprised when he rushed into our bedroom and as fast as lightning emerged with a
 heap of clothes. <#/>He started hurling them outside. <#/>My underclothes were displayed. <#/>Oh how embarrassing it was! <#/>I did not know where to look. <#/>They begged him to stop but he refused. <#/>Embarrassed and disgusted, they walked away in pro
test."
\par <#/>"What were your feelings towards him after that?" I asked curiously.
\par <#/>"I still loved him," she responded calmly and went on. <#/>"I remember when one evening after this incident, he roughed
 me up. <#/>That was three years ago. <#/>He was drunk. <#/>On entering the house, he went straight for the kitchen knife. <#/>I had not the slightest idea why he was so furious. <#/>To ensure that I did not run away, he locked all the doors. <#/>He heade
d for me. <#/>I dodged. <#/>He chased me all over the house until he pinned me into }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_article>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 corner . <#/>He grinned. <#/>`Yes you thought you were clever,' he bellowed triumphantly.
\par <#/>"I struggled but could not free myself. <#/>He prepared to thrust t
he knife into me. <#/>I was about to scream when he slipped over a piece of ripe banana our daughter had dropped on the floor. <#/>He fell down with a big thud! <#/>I took that chance to pick up the knife and hurled it out of the window. <#/>I ran to the 
b
athroom and locked myself in. <#/>The fact that I had escaped infuriated him so much that he cursed and called me names. <#/>He kicked and violently banged the bathroom door. <#/>Thank God the door never gave way otherwise I do not think I would have live
d to tell this story.
\par <#/>"Mad with anger, Jared gave up. <#/>He collapsed on the floor. <#/>It did not take ten minutes before he started snoring. <#/>I stealthily opened the door and there he was! <#/>Crumpled in a heap on the floor near the bathroom door
. <#/>I looked at him lying there. <#/>I was filled with pity and love for him. <#/>I remembered our early days of courtship and felt nostalgic. <#/>I tried to carry him to the bedroom but he was too heavy for me. <#/>I decided to take off his shoes and c
over him with a blanket. <#/>The following morning, he behaved as if nothing had happened."
\par <#/>"I don't understand why you have hung on," I interrupted, realising that Lucy was determined to pour out all her heart to me.
\par <#/>She continued as if she had not
 heard me, "As if what he had done to me so far was not enough, one afternoon when I came home from the market, he roughly got hold of me, pinned me down and snarled at me, `Why did you take this long at the market? <#/>What were you doing? <#/>How many m
e
n did you sleep with?' He did not give me time to answer him. <#/>He hit me so hard on the head that I passed out. <#/>When I came to I found myself in the bathroom with Jared holding me. <#/>I was not able to struggle with him but I vividly remember what
 he did to me."
\par <#/>Lucy hesitated a bit. <#/>I encouraged her to continue.
\par <#/>"He ... <#/>he pulled my clothing up to my chest. <#/>He removed my underwear - everything. <#/>In his left hand, he had a torch. <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>I could not guess what he was up to. <#
/>To my horror and shame, he examined me! <#/>This he did to check whether I had actually slept with a man or not. <#/>I have never felt so humiliated in my life," Lucy concluded.
\par <#/>"How does he treat your children?" I asked, shaken.
\par <#/>"He is very loving to them," she replied.
\par <#/>"Then what could be his problem?" I wondered aloud.
\par <#/>I suggested that she starts some kind of business so that she could contribute to the family finances.
\par <#/>"Supposing I gave you some small capital to help you start?" I offered.
\par <#/>Lucy was such a strong-willed, strong-hearted woman that it took me time to convince her to accept money from me. <#/>She eventually accepted and I knew she would succeed in whatever she ventured to do.
\par <#/>"I would like to request something," she started.
\par <#/>"Yes, please."
\par <#/>"Why don't you help me to keep some of my profits?" she said, adding, "I have done some business before and I was unable to save anything because Jared asked for the money every day. <#/>I want you to keep it a secret. 
<#/>If he knows about it, we shall both be in trouble."
\par <#/>I found Lucy's request quite risky but I accepted to }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>idiom}{\v\fs24\lang2057  help her.
\par <#/>We sat silently for a while, each person lost in her thoughts. <#/>Lucy suddenly looked at me, and asked, "What do you think about divorce?"
\par <#/>This was the last question I expected from Lucy. <#/>She had all along shown great determination to hang on to her marriage. <#/>I was aware that my opinion on divorce might influence her, so I quickly threw the question back to h
er," What do you think about it yourself?"
\par <#/>She hesitated a little and then said, "I personally have hated anything to do with divorce. <#/>I shudder at the thought of it. <#/>My biggest wish in life has been to cling to my marriage for the sake of my c
hildren. <#/>I have sworn never to divorce. <#/>It painfully reminds me of my suffering as a child. <#/>I do not want my children to suffer as I did."
\par <#/>After that fateful night, Lucy's life returned to normal and she even began to look around for some a
ctivity that could generate income as we had discussed. <#/>But before she could get started, she received a letter inviting her to join a teacher training college. <#/>As she told me later, she had applied several times without success but she had never 
given up.
\par <#/>Not very surprisingly, her husband was not very keen on her going away to college but she was determined not to lose this opportunity. <#/>Her father assisted her with all the financial requirements and she soon went to the college, leaving Ja
red with their two children.
\par <#/>One day, while she was at college, their son, Peter, was taken very ill with fever. <#/>Jared was out watching a football match. <#/>When I was informed about it, I decided to take him to hospital. <#/>When Jared arrived an
d was told what had happened, he immediately followed us to the hospital. <#/>He met us on our way back. <#/>I clearly saw that he was very grateful for what I had done.
\par <#/>"Oh! Mama Anne, I don't know how to thank you! <#/>When I left the house early thi
s afternoon this boy was fine!" he said with appreciation as he took his son in his arms. <#/>When we reached his house, I gave him his child's medicine and told him I would drop in later to check on his progress.
\par <#/>That evening I went back to check on Peter and was happy to find him playing. <#/>Jared offered me a seat.
\par <#/>"Mama Anne," he addressed me.
\par <#/>"Yes!" I responded.
\par <#/>"I have always wanted to complain to you about your friend, Lucy."
\par <#/>"I see," I answered, not knowing what else to say.
\par <#/>I saw this as the golden chance I had wished to have so that I could ask him why they fought so often.
\par <#/>"Your friend is a very bad woman," he continued. <#/>"Her mother was divorced because she was loose. <#/>All her stepsisters are not properly mar
ried. <#/>They work as bar-maids. <#/>I just have no confidence in Lucy. <#/>She is like all of them! <#/>I had hardly known her well when I was forced to marry her," he said with a tone of bitterness.
